verdicts.recommended_action:
Fix applySpawn (mc/verbs/dispatchverb.go:359-367) to honor ADR-020 D4 — populate the snapshot from whichever field the Editor mode filled:

    var pool []int64
    switch sp.Role {
    case dispatch.RoleEditor:
        pool = sp.ProposedPool
    case dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview:
        pool = sp.Wave // ADR-020 D4: the id set this run was shown and must act on exactly
    }
    if pool == nil && (sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditor || sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview) {
        pool = []int64{}
    }

(Keep the nil -> []int64{} normalization so an Editor run always writes a non-NULL snapshot; a plan-review wave is never empty when dispatched, since planReviewPending requires an open unreviewed child.)

Close the two blind spots that let this ship green — both are the real defect here, since the code was never exercised on its production path:
1. Extend dvAssertEffect's `case dispatch.KindSpawn` (mc/verbs/dispatchverb_test.go:152-169) to assert the persisted `runs.pool_snapshot`, not just `got["pool_ids"]`.
2. Add an end-to-end regression that calls the real `Dispatch(db)` on dvUnreviewedWave's spine, then drives `EditorPlanReview` with the run id it actually returns — covering BOTH arms (pass reaches plan_reviewed=1; send-back actually cancels the children). Do not reuse claimPlanReview (mc/cmd/mc/cli_test.go:4912), whose hand-inserted row is what hid the bug.

Since ADR-020's design was already reviewed and is correct, this is an implementation gap only — log it per AGENTS.md §6 (log-and-go: no invariant is broken by the ADR, only by the code), no operator input needed.

Fix at mc/verbs/dispatchverb.go:361-367 — populate the snapshot for the plan-review mode too, honoring D4's "whichever of the two the Editor mode populated":

```go
var pool []int64
switch sp.Role {
case dispatch.RoleEditor:
    pool = sp.ProposedPool
case dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview:
    pool = sp.Wave
}
if pool == nil && (sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditor || sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview) {
    pool = []int64{}
}
```
I verified this exact change makes the pass arm mark both children and the send-back arm drain the initiative (next tick correctly becomes strategist(initiative)); no other change was required.

Add the missing seam test — the real defect is that the fast suite is green with this live. The plan-review terminal tests must reach the lease through `verbs.Dispatch`/`applySpawn` instead of `claimPlanReview`'s faked `INSERT INTO runs (... pool_snapshot)` (cli_test.go:4914). At minimum one test asserting `runs.pool_snapshot` is non-NULL and equals the wave after a real plan-review spawn, and one round-trip Dispatch→EditorPlanReview(pass)→children dispatch. Consider keeping the fake helper for the fence/verdict matrix but pinning the seam separately.

Secondary, worth a decision but not part of this finding: dispatchverb.go:382 `poolIDs := sp.ProposedPool` still reports `pool_ids=[]` in the spawn effect for a plan review, which the resident copies into `run.json`. D4 only specifies `runs.pool_snapshot`, so this may be intentional — but if `run.json`'s `pool_ids` is meant to mirror the id set the run must act on, it has the same one-mode gap and should be settled explicitly rather than by omission.

Fix the writer at mc/verbs/dispatchverb.go:359-367 to carry the wave for the plan-review mode, as D4 specifies ("passes whichever of the two the Editor mode populated"):

    var pool []int64
    switch sp.Role {
    case dispatch.RoleEditor:
        pool = sp.ProposedPool
    case dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview:
        pool = sp.Wave
    }
    if sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditor || sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview {
