Then close the seam the test suite fakes, which is the actual root cause — the bug is invisible only because applySpawn has zero test coverage (`git grep applySpawn -- "*_test.go"` is empty) while cli_test.go:4913 `claimPlanReview` hand-inserts the snapshot. Add a verbs test that drives the REAL path end-to-end — seed a seeded initiative with two unreviewed children, call verbs.Dispatch(db), assert `runs.pool_snapshot` for the returned run_id equals the wave (not NULL), and assert domain.PassWaveReview succeeds against `runPoolSnapshot`'s result. This test must go red on the current code before the fix lands (AGENTS.md §3, red-first).

Also add a send-back arm test on the real seam: it must fail today by reporting success while cancelling zero children. Consider making SendBackWave defensive — an empty snapshot on an initiative with open children is never a legitimate state (planReviewPending guarantees at least one open unreviewed child), so it should return an error rather than silently succeed; that would have converted this silent livelock into a loud failure.

Per AGENTS.md §6 this is log-and-go, not a park: it breaks no operator-only decision. Record it in IMPLEMENTATION-NOTES.md — the ADR-020 Status block's claim that "D1-D5 are green on the fast lane" is falsified and should be corrected, since the green suite never exercised the write side.

Fix both, but keep them distinct and fix them in order.

1. PRIMARY (the sibling finding, and the actual live bug): repair the applySpawn seam at mc/verbs/dispatchverb.go:361-367 so the plan-review mode's snapshot reaches the claim, per ADR-020 D4:
    var pool []int64
    switch sp.Role {
    case dispatch.RoleEditor:
        pool = sp.ProposedPool
    case dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview:
        pool = sp.Wave
    }
    if pool == nil && (sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditor || sp.Role == dispatch.RoleEditorPlanReview) {
        pool = []int64{}
    }
This alone turns today's silent live-lock into correct behavior.

2. THIS FINDING (defense in depth, cheap, fails closed for the right reason): after the cancellation loop in SendBackWave (mc/domain/initiative.go:158), re-read openChildIDs and refuse whole — never partially apply — unless it is empty, i.e. assert D5's own postcondition instead of trusting the snapshot. The transaction is the atomicity boundary, so returning an error rolls back cleanly and the lease rules recover the run.

3. Pin both with the tests ADR-020 already owes ("Tests that pin it" -> Verbs): the existing test asserts the send-back "cancels open children with actor='editor' ... drains the initiative", but it evidently constructs runs.pool_snapshot directly rather than going through a real dispatch — which is why the seam slipped through. Add a differential test that spawns via applySpawn and asserts runs.pool_snapshot is non-NULL and equals the wave, plus a SendBackWave unit test asserting a nil/partial snapshot errors rather than returning nil.

Note for the ADR record: D5's send-back text ("this arm asserts nothing about the set, it destroys it") is what licensed the unchecked loop. Worth a one-line clarification that the license covers *individual already-archived members*, not the set as a whole, and that the drained postcondition is asserted.
